        <h1><i class="icon-th"></i> Grid System</h1>
        <p>The <!-- $siteName --> grid system supports a variable number of columns per row and supports fractions from halves through twelfths out of the box. Column widths can be specifed with classes (i.e. <code>one half</code>, <code>three fourths</code>, or <code>two fifths</code>) or without classes using <a href="http://sass-lang.com/docs/yardoc/file.SASS_REFERENCE.html#extend" target="_blank">@extend</a> with <a href="http://sass-lang.com/docs/yardoc/file.SASS_REFERENCE.html#placeholder_selectors_" target="_blank">placeholder selectors</a> to achieve pure semantic implementations.</p>
        <h6>Example usage:</h6>
        <script src="https://gist.github.com/ghepting/5282665.js"></script>
        <noscript><p class="error callout">Javascript is required to display Gist from Github</p></noscript>
        <h6>Result:</h6>
        <div class="demo">
          <div class="row">
            <div class="two thirds">1st</div>
            <div class="one third">2nd</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <hr/>
        
        <h4 class="double gap-top">Responsive Adjustments</h4>
        <p>By default, columns collapse into seperate rows when viewport width is below 768 pixels. To achieve column layouts on smaller screens, you can apply <code>small-tablet</code> or <code>mobile</code>.</p>
        <h6>Example usage:</h6>
        <script src="https://gist.github.com/ghepting/5282668.js"></script>
        <noscript><p class="error callout">Javascript is required to display Gist from Github</p></noscript>
        <h6>Result:</h6>
        <div class="demo">
          <div class="row">
            <div class="one mobile half">1st</div>
            <div class="one mobile half">2nd</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="small">Note: Resizing the viewport to mobile proportions will not collapse these columns.</p>
        <hr/>
        
        <h4 class="double gap-top">Equal Height Columns</h4>
        <p>Equal height columns without using a <code>&lt;table&gt;</code> is something that is unexpectedly difficult to achieve with CSS in its current state. <!-- $siteName --> comes with a helpful, lightweight Javascript component that makes this easy.</p>
        <h6>Example Usage:</h6>
        <script src="https://gist.github.com/ghepting/5285384.js"></script>
        <noscript><p class="error callout">Javascript is required to display Gist from Github</p></noscript>
        <h6>Result:</h6>
        <div class="equal-columns demo">
          <div class="row equalize">
            <div class="one half"><h1>Column One</h1></div>
            <div class="one half"><h1>Column Two</h1><p>With some extra stuff</p></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="two thirds padded">
        <!-- start demo grid -->
        <h2>Semantic, Fractional Column Sizing</h2>
        <p>One of the key features of <!-- $siteName --> is the responsive, fractions-based, nestable fluid grid system. Utilizing semantic class names and boasting built-in support for purely semantic implementations using selector inheritance (<code>@extend</code>) and mixins (<code>@include</code>), the grid system has been engineered to be the last grid you will ever need. You can easily optimize it to fit your specific needs and customize the range of fractions that it supports. There are three variable strings in the <code><a href="https://github.com/groundworkcss/groundwork/blob/master/src/scss/_grid.scss" target="_blank">src/scss/_grid.scss</a></code> file that you can modify:</p>
        <script src="https://gist.github.com/ghepting/5311695.js"></script>
        <noscript><p class="error callout">Javascript is required to display Gist from Github</p></noscript>
        <p>By default, the grid system supports <em>wholes</em> through <em>twelfths</em> to achieve a high level of flexibility. However, it is highly recommended that you fine tune it to the specific needs of each project. If you only use thirds, for example, removing the unused numerators/denominators will greatly reduce the output CSS filesize. Note that these space-delimited string variables are used as arrays and are looped through, so having the proper numerators (<code>$numbers</code>) and denominators (<code>$fractions</code> &amp; <code>$fractions_plural</code>) for each fractional step in the total range is required.</p>
        <hr/>

